\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

\lang american
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{R}^{n}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be a twice continuously differentiable function such that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\forall x\in\mathbb{R}^{n}:\nabla^{2}f\left(x\right)\succ0
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 be a stationary point of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, meaning:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nabla f\left(x\right)=0_{n}
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in R^{n}$
\end_inset

 such that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y\neq x
\]

\end_inset

Denote 
\begin_inset Formula $r=1.1\cdot\left\Vert y-x\right\Vert _{2}$
\end_inset

 and the ball 
\begin_inset Formula $B\left(x,r\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We know that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\noindent

\lang american
\begin_inset Formula $B\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\noindent

\lang american
\begin_inset Formula $y\in B$
\end_inset

 (since 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert y-x\right\Vert _{2}<1.1\left\Vert y-x\right\Vert _{2}=r$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

\lang american
In addition, 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is twice continuously differentiable over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 ,hence, by a the linear approximation theorem:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\exists\xi\in\left[x,y\right] & :\\
 & f\left(y\right)=f\left(x\right)+\underbrace{\nabla f\left(x\right)^{T}}_{0_{n}}\left(y-x\right)+\frac{1}{2}\left(y-x\right)^{T}\nabla^{2}f\left(\xi\right)\left(y-x\right)\\
 & =f\left(x\right)+\frac{1}{2}\underbrace{\left(y-x\right)^{T}\nabla^{2}f\left(\xi\right)\left(y-x\right)}_{\left(*\right)>0}\\
 & >f\left(x\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

\lang american
hence:
\end_layout

