\lang english
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is twice continuously differentiable function over 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 ,hence all combined partial derivatives are continuous over 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, meaning that each cell in the hessian, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla^{2}f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is a continuous function of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

\lang english
Let's take an arbitrary vector 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in R^{n}$
\end_inset

 and define the function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g\left(x\right):U\longrightarrow\mathbb{R}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g\left(x\right)=y^{T}\nabla^{2}f\left(x\right)y=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\sum_{j=1}^{n}\left(\nabla^{2}f\left(x\right)\right)_{i,j}y_{i}y_{j}
\]

\end_inset

As we can see, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is a linear combination of the cells of the hessian, meaning it is a linear
 combination of continuous functions over 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and hence continuous by itself over 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

\lang english
In addition, in the point 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{0}\in U$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g\left(x^{0}\right)=y^{T}\nabla^{2}f\left(x^{0}\right)y>0
\]

\end_inset

because:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nabla^{2}f\left(x^{0}\right)\succ0
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is a continuous function over 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 , and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x^{0}\right)>0$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\exists r>0:\forall x\in B\left(x^{0},r\right)\hspace{1em}g\left(x\right)>0
\]

\end_inset

therefore:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\exists r>0:\forall x\in B\left(x^{0},r\right)\hspace{1em}y^{T}\nabla^{2}f\left(x\right)y>0
\]

\end_inset


